            <h2>Willan</h2>
            <p><span class="initial-letter darkorange-text">T</span>he final irregular verb is '<em>willan - to
                    want</em>'. Though '<em>willan</em>' looks like it could be translated to 'will', and it is
                where the modern word 'will' comes from, translate it as 'want' or 'intend' in the present tense.
                When in the past tense, it can be translated as either 'wanted' or 'would'.
            </p>
            <p>
                '<em>Willan</em>' often comes paired with the infinitive form of another verb, just like in modern
                English.
                For example, I want to go, you want to see, he wants to drink. Examine the sentences '<em>Ic wille
                    gangan to Rome - I want to go to Rome</em>' and '<em>He wolde ðæt ða cnihtas cræft leornedon - He
                    wanted the children to learn a craft</em>'.
            </p>
